{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2011}} {{Infobox Officeholder | name=Lyman Enos Knapp | image name=Lyman Enos Knapp.jpg | office=3rd Governor of [[District of Alaska]] | term_start=April 20, 1889 | term_end=August 29, 1893 | nominator= [[Benjamin Harrison]] | predecessor=[[Alfred P. Swineford]] | successor=[[James Sheakley]] | birth_date={{birth date|1837|11|5}} | birth_place= [[Somerset, Vermont|Somerset]], Vermont | death_date={{death date and age|1904|10|9|1837|11|5}} | death_place=[[Seattle]], [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] | residence= | spouse=Martha A Severance | profession=Journalist, Lawyer | religion= | party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] |}}
'''Lyman Enos Knapp''' (November 5, 1837 – October 9, 1904) was an American [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician who was the [[List of Governors of Alaska|Governor]] of the [[District of Alaska]] from 1889 to 1893. He was also a member of the [[Vermont House of Representatives]] from 1884 to 1885. He was born in [[Somerset, Vermont]] and died in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]].
==Background== Knapp was born November 5, 1837 in [[Somerset, Vermont]] to Hiram and Elvira (Stearns) Knapp.<ref name="Brown">{{cite book |last=Brown |first=John Howard |title=The Cyclopaedia of American Biography |publisher=James H. Lamb|year=1901 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=WLTByjPIkCwC&pg=PA578|pages=578}}</ref> He was educated in [[Manchester (town), Vermont|Manchester, Vermont]], first attending Burr and Burton Seminary and then graduating with a Bachelor of Arts from [[Middlebury College]] in 1862.<ref name="McMullin & Walker">{{cite book |last=McMullin |first=Thomas A. |last2=Walker |first2=David |title=Biographical Directory of American Territorial Governors |publisher=Meckler Publishing|location=Westport, CT |year=1984 | isbn = 0-930466-11-X | pages=6–7}}</ref> With the [[American Civil War]] being under way at the time of his graduation, Knapp enlisted as a [[Private (rank)|private]] in the Company I, [[16th Vermont Infantry]] and was quickly promoted to [[Captain (United States)|captain]] of Company F, [[17th Vermont Infantry]].<ref name="J.T. White">{{cite book |author=James T. White & Company |title=The National cyclopaedia of American biography |volume=vol XII|publisher=J. T. White & Company|location=New York |year=1904 | oclc = 17692533 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=TnNMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA355 |pages=355–6}}</ref> During his military service, he was wounded at [[Battle of Gettysburg|Gettysburg]], [[Battle of Spotsylvania Court House|Spotsylvania]], and [[Siege of Petersburg|Petersburg]]. Knapp rose to the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|lieutenant colonel]] and was [[brevetted]] a [[Colonel (United States)|colonel]] for his gallantry during the Siege of Petersburg.<ref name="Brown"/> On January 23, 1865, Knapp married Martha A Severance of [[Middlebury, Vermont]]. The couple had four children.<ref name="J.T. White"/>
Following the war, Knapp returned to Vermont where he published the [[Middlebury, Vermont|Middlebury]] ''Register'' from 1865 till 1878.<ref name="McMullin & Walker"/> In addition to the work on his own newspaper, he submitted articles to the Chicago ''Inter-Ocean'' and the ''American Law Register''.<ref name="Brown"/> Beyond his journalistic efforts, Knapp served as Clerk of the [[Vermont Legislature]] during the 1872-3 session. After being [[admitted to the bar]] in 1876, he served as a [[probate judge]] for the [[Addison County, Vermont|Addison district]] from 1879–89.<ref name="McMullin & Walker"/> Knapp was also elected for a term in the [[Vermont House of Representatives]] from 1884 to 1885.<ref name="Herringshaw">{{cite book |first = Thomas William | last = Herringshaw |title=Herringshaw's national library of American biography |volume=vol III|publisher=American Publishers' Association|location=Chicago |year=1914 | oclc = 3152314 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=gRQ9AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA437 |pages=437}}</ref>
==Governorship== Knapp was appointed Governor of the District of Alaska by President [[Benjamin Harrison]], his term beginning on April 20, 1889. At the time of his appointment, many Alaskans desired a resident governor and were disappointed receiving an "outsider". The district did however see a number of improvements during his administration. Postal service was extended with the creation of over {{convert|1600|mi|km}} of new mail routes. Knapp also helped establish a historical society and library.<ref name="J.T. White"/>
On the legal front, Knapp asked for Alaska to be granted a [[Delegate (United States Congress)|Delegate to the U.S. Congress]]. He also supported creation of a commission to revise the district's [[legal code]] and, arguing that lack of clear land possession discouraged improvements, lobbied for a revision of the land possession laws.<ref name="McMullin & Walker"/> To help maintain law and order, Knapp help organize both a [[militia]] and Indian police.<ref name="J.T. White"/> The former turned into a source of amusement for some area residents due to the governor's predilection for dressing in his military uniform and watch the militia [[Military parade|parade]] before him.<ref name="McMullin & Walker"/>
During his term, an international dispute over [[seal fisheries]] reached a zenith.<ref name="J.T. White"/> The United States, claiming that seals from Alaska were being killed by Canadian and other ships on the high seas, had seized several ships and brought them to [[Sitka, Alaska|Sitka]]. Arbitration to resolve the dispute was agreed to in 1891 between Canada, the United Kingdom, and the United States. As a result a set of restrictions was imposed on seal hunting near Alaska.<ref name="McMullin & Walker"/> Knapp was replaced as governor on August 29, 1893 following the appointment of [[James Sheakley]] by President [[Grover Cleveland]].<ref name="McMullin & Walker"/>
==After office== Following his term as governor, Knapp moved to [[Seattle]] and opened a law practice.<ref name="Brown"/> He was active in civil organizations such as the Institute of Civics and [[National Geographic Society]] and received an Honorary [[LL.D.]] from [[Whitman College]] in 1893.<ref name="J.T. White"/> Knapp was also the founder and President of the [[Anti-Saloon League]] of Washington. He remained active in the practice of law until his death on October 9, 1904.<ref name="McMullin & Walker"/>
